post_text:
With meal delivery being free for all families, we've noticed that most people aren't submitting a free and reduced lunch application. We wanted to encourage folks to fill one out anyway -- the information not only helps our schools, but your student could be missing out on benefits without realizing it!

Free and reduced lunch data is a funding source for many things in a school district, and can provide partial funding for internet for our families that qualify for free and reduced.
Interventionists in schools are paid for using this funding, and high school students who qualify can receive Running Start fee waivers, college application waivers, and AP course fee waivers.
Many grants and athletic fees also use this information to determine eligibility.

There are lots of benefits to filling out an application! Visit our Nutrition Services page below for more information!

https://www.cheneysd.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=509909&type=d&pREC_ID=1032270

Hotline Resource for Families: 509-559-4375
A district helpline has been created to support families as we begin the school year in a distance learning model. The helpline will be live starting Wednesday, September 9 and will be available on school days from 8:00 a.m. – 7:00 p.m. This resource will be staffed with district staff members who will be available to answer questions related to technology and learning needs. The helpline contains a variety of menu options that will help us provide the appropriate support and resources. Families can also leave a message outside of daily scheduled times and a return response will be provided within 24 hours. Call 509-559-4375 for support.

post_text: It's that time of year again -- the Cheney Helping Cheney Coat Drive! The coat drive will be only be able to accept new coats this year. Coats can be dropped off at Copy Junction, 1921 1st Street in Cheney, now through October 12. Distribution will begin Wednesday, October 14 at Cheney Outreach, 616 3rd Street. There is no qualifying criteria to get coats. Anyone who wants or needs coats can get them during Outreach hours, Monday 4 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. and Wednesday 8:30 a.m. - 2 p.m. If you have gently used coats, the Cheney Clothing Exchange is accepting clean used coats every other Wednesday from noon until 6 p.m. Thank you to the Kiwanis and to Copy Junction for helping with this annual event. Let’s keep Cheney warm this winter!

Families,

Last week we sent out a registration form link for families to complete for each of their Cheney Public Schools students. The link to this registration form has now been deactivated. The information gathered will assist us in determining how to staff classrooms. Thank you to those of you that completed a registration form for your student(s). If you did not have the opportunity to complete the registration form for your student(s) you will be receiving a phone call from your child’s school in the next few days asking for this information.

We know this is a confusing and trying time as you prepare to have your children educated in a different yet temporary setting. Please also know that we are doing everything we can to make this experience as seamless as possible.

Your child's school is now open for phone calls and questions if you have any.

Helen Page
Assistant to the Superintendent

July 20, 2020

Parents, Guardians, and Staff Members,

In an effort to assist the district in understanding the number of parents who would prefer some form of on-site instruction in the fall, and those who would prefer a strictly on-line option, we emailed a second parent survey on Friday, July 17th. It is critical that we have as many parents as possible complete the survey so that we have accurate data to analyze as part of our ongoing planning process (as of this morning we have received 2,887 responses). Therefore, I am urging each of you to take a few minutes to complete the survey prior to 4:00 p.m. this afternoon.

If you have any questions related to the survey, please contact our district office at 509-559-4502.

Have a great day!

Rob Roettger, Superintendent

Survey Link: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfIHa8pB3qnGe4yP7MpjtZ1V1CKoCp7j89Ww5dYSVF7bR7zfA/viewform?usp=sf_link

post_text: This is a historic, emotional time in our country and in our community. We struggle to find the words to express the sadness we feel at the senseless loss of all those who have lost their lives as a result of violence and racism. Our communities across the nation are being called upon to make positive changes, and we are committed to working, partnering and leading that change at Cheney Public Schools and beyond. We believe in the power of knowledge and education to help bring about the social transformations we all seek, and as such will be renewing our efforts to engage in consistent self-reflection, ensure culturally relevant teaching, participate in professional development opportunities to improve cultural competence, and continue to engage in vital community conversations. To any students who are struggling during this time, please don't hesitate to reach out to us, to each other, and to our community. Us, we, together.

Parents and Guardians,

You are invited to take part in a Thoughtexchange survey to provide feedback about the continuous learning model students have been engaged in since the school building closure in March. We value the thoughts and ideas parents and guardians have regarding student learning. Please take a few minutes to access the survey link below and we encourage you to return to the survey again prior to the closing date of June 5 to rate the thoughts of others.

Thank you in advance for participating.

Rob Roettger, Superintendent

post_text:
We have received many questions about yearbooks during this time, and we want to reassure everyone we ARE having yearbooks this year!

We are still working on the specifics so that they are created and distributed as safely as possible. We've been working diligently to make sure the book is the best it can be and covers our students' lives this year in an accurate and historical way. We know it is taking longer than expected, but we want to do this right for our student body (and are somewhat restricted by outside shipping dates that are out of our hands). Our Yearbook supervisor, Editor-In-Chief, and class are working together and have lots of ideas on how to continue the yearbook tradition, distribute them and allow students to access them.

The yearbook tradition will continue and stay true this year, and if anyone is still looking to purchase a book, we do have limited copies remaining. The book is currently $60 and can be purchased online at www.jostensyearbooks.com on a first come, first serve basis. Thank you so much for your patience as we navigate Yearbook during this time!

post_text: During the ongoing school closure, Cheney Public Schools is partnering with Cheney Parks & Recreation to provide drop-in childcare services for students aged four years through fifth-grade. The drop-in services are available from 8:00am through 3:30pm, Monday through Friday and the theme is “Castles, Knights and Dragons.” Our focus is to provide service for families of first responders and healthcare workers. School district staff are implementing guidance from the CDC and the Regional Health District regarding safety, health and cleaning protocols, including limiting access to the building and monitoring the health of all children and staff members prior to entry. If your family's circumstances have changed or if you believe you qualify and are still in need of childcare, please complete the childcare survey for more information (https://forms.gle/suJLeinHATEyZ2ZJ9) or call the Family/Community Question Line at (509) 559-4580.

Continued academic resources for our students has been a major focus of ours and our families, and we're glad to announce that our teacher teams have prepared online resources for at-home learning that students and families may access to maintain learning and further develop skills already taught by classroom teachers. These can be accessed on our website and will be handed out at food drop-off locations starting on Tuesday. post_text:
To Cheney School District's families, students and community:
Gov. Jay Inslee announced today that he is mandating the closure of all Washington schools from March 17, through at least April 24.
District leadership is at this very moment meeting and formulating plans to move forward with this new development.
As this situation evolves, it will undoubtedly affect all of us. We are all learning about it, and we appreciate that we are all coming together to do that in collaborative and respectful ways – understanding that disruptions that may occur in the short-term will have a beneficial effect in the longer term – for everyone. We will keep you updated with all relevant information and, while we recognize that many questions will occur, we are committed to addressing each of those to the best of our ability and resources.
We will update with more information as soon as possible.

post_text:
Westwood Middle School's RoboGo team competed at Lakeside High School recently and took home first place! Courses this year included bot navigation and three mazes. These courses required a precisely coded bot to navigate obstacles without going out of bounds.
Awards for the school or team with the highest points:
Team "Teamama" (Haley Van Norman and Karsten Harvey) had two flawless runs through the navigation course and received a 2nd place trophy for highest team points, following a timed tiebreaker between WMS and another school since they both had two perfect scores.
Haley and Karsten had the idea of free coding through the mazes with speed and distance measurements vs. using sensors. No other students attempted this approach and it gave them the best times through the maze.
Ethan Quay took 2nd place for best navigation. He scored perfect first navigation run and a near-perfect second run. He also was perfect through the maze.
All teams that participated had at least one perfect run through the navigation course. Westwood showed great sportsmanship and teamwork!

STATEOFCHILDHOODOBESITY.ORG
Eastern Washington Schools Make Meals Healthier

Empire Health Foundation
February 27 at 11:49 AM ·

Childhood obesity prevention was our first strategic initiative as an organization. Through support from the state and collaborative partnerships with regional school districts such as Cheney Public Schools, we have seen a 4.5% statistically significant decline in body mass index (BMI) among children who had been overweight or obese through scratch cooking.

This programmatically and financially sustainable project is “changing lives one school lunch at a time.” Read more below.

Since it's National Counseling Week, we thought we'd share this message from some of our elementary counselors!
"It's National School Counseling Week! The Elementary School Counselors in Cheney Public Schools are committed to the personal, social, academic and career needs of ALL students. We work in collaboration with teachers, staff, families and the community to further the development of our students into strong contributing members of society. We can be found teaching core personal/social curriculum in the classroom, working with small groups, doing short term work with individual students or collaborating with stakeholders. We love our students!"

post_text:
Over the weekend, Cheney Middle School hosted the Eastern Washington Braille Challenge, presented by the Washington Talking Book & Braille Library. There, blind and visually impaired children and their families could test their braille literacy and find resources from United Blind of Spokane and Lilac Services for the Blind.
One of the highlights of the day was a visit and presentation from Guide Dogs for the Blind.They offer several programs, including the Canine Buddy program, which places career change dogs (puppies no longer undergoing guide dog training) with blind and visually impaired children to help them learn how to live in a home with a large dog.
Russell Winkler, 9, and Maddi Lund, 8, were so excited to pet the pups, and we were so excited to be a part of it! #connectingcommunities

Westwood students from the National Junior Honor Society volunteered with Second Harvest Food Bank on Friday and sorted almost 20,000 pounds of corn and pears!
The Washington state valuation of a volunteer hour is $31.72. In the two shifts worked on Dec. 13, our students contributed $3,700 worth of volunteering.
Second Harvest provides food to people in need in 26 counties in Eastern Washington and Northern Idaho. Since 2016, WMS's National Junior Honor Society has volunteered more than 700 hours there.

Students from Ms. Alvick’s social studies class at Westwood Middle School have been simulating the characteristics of civilization, including the “founding” and “construction” of their very own Sumer! Students broke into the traditional Sumerian social structure to create a stable food supply, a government, the arts, and specific constructions that the people in Sumer would have made.
Students pictured are “training for the army” (directed by General Maya De La Cruz), crafting “laws” (written by Vizier Ethan Martin) and constructing “irrigation systems” for the civilization.

Schreiber's career dreams came true when he joined the U.S. Army as a cyber operations specialist. After enlisting out of Cheney Army Recruiting Station, Schreiber completed Basic Combat Training and is now attending Advanced Individual Training.

post_text:
Cheney Public Schools is pleased to announce that Betz Elementary School teacher Traci Trotter has been selected as Eastern Washington University’s Teacher of the Month.

In an assembly at Betz Elementary School on Friday, Nov. 21, representatives from KHQ Local News and Spokane Teachers Credit Union presented Ms. Trotter with the honor in an exciting surprise ceremony in front of the student body. Ms. Trotter teaches first grade and was nominated by fourth-grader Avery Pringle – three years after he was in her class.

“I didn’t cry but I was crying inside,” Pringle said. “She’s kind and helps any student she can. I’ll never forget her.”

Ms. Trotter has been teaching for seven years and credited her students for inspiring her. “They’re why I do it,” she said.

Students in Mrs. Mobley’s Interior Design class are taking on the challenge of redesigning the staff room at CHS. The building has a budget of about $5,000 to spend on staff work environment, so Mrs. Mobley tasked her class with reimagining the area.
Students developed presentations, design boards, and a budget to present to the class. Mr. Heuett and Mrs. Delcore are attending the presentations to get ideas from the students.
This is a great, hands-on example of students work and learning being put into practice! It will be exciting for them to see which of their ideas make it into the final design!

post_text:
Ready to restore your faith in humanity? An amazing partnership has formed between two classes in our District!
Westwood Middle School CTE teacher Marty Sexton and Windsor Kindergarten teacher Judy Ableman have teamed up to help our District's youngest students have a happy holiday.
Mrs. Ableman sent Mr. Sexton the names of her kindergartners and their favorite animals, and his second period woodshop class (made up of 7th and 8th graders) is now in the midst of custom-carving those names, along with a puzzle version of the chosen animal!
The class will be giving these gifts to Mrs. Ableman's students right before Christmas. Some older students, like Macey pictured above, are making two sets to give away.
Such a sweet gesture that also gives students a hands-on learning opportunity. So proud of Cheney's teachers and students!

We love fall! Members of the Cheney High School Key Club, a student-led organization whose goal is to encourage leadership through serving others, spent a day this week doing "Rake and Run" community service.
Students walked through the neighborhoods of Cheney raking as many leaves as they could, then bagged them up and took them to the recycling center!
We're so proud of everyone who participated. Volunteering in the community has been shown to build empathy, develop leadership skills, and even improve academic performance.
Thanks, Key Club! What's your favorite way to volunteer?

post_text:
From the Wolverine Pride volunteers:
A growing problem in our country is opioid addiction. Every day, more than 130 people die from overdosing on opioids in the United States and most opiod abuse starts from using other people’s prescriptions. People have recognized this as a problem and have established a National Take Back Day. There are a number of stations across the country where you can drop off unused prescription drugs. For the first time, the DEA will also accept vape cartridges or devices. To contribute to the National Take Back Day, Wolverine Pride unboxed prescription drug lock boxes, inserted directions, and prepared them for the Take Back event in Airway Heights, where people could get the lock boxes for free.

This weekend, 12 Cheney High School students worked on three different teams to compete in this year’s CyberPatriot competition.The competition featured over 5,000 teams across the nation and over 50 from Washington.
Our top team placed top 15 in the first round while the other two teams were in 20th and 27th!
The CyberPatriot competition requires students understand how computers work and vulnerabilities in the operating systems. It is a 6-hour hands-on event and students learn the importance of maintaining safe computer habits.
Great job to all our competitors!

On Thursday night, students from Cheney High School's Advanced Culinary Arts class got the chance to experience a real kitchen. Students got to go into the kitchen at Bene's in Cheney to help prepare food for the Football Team Dinner.
Bene's owner Derek welcomed the students into his kitchen, coached them in preparing the meal, and showed them how to serve what they prepared.
Thanks to Derek and to Mrs. Green and Mrs. Byrd for setting up such a great opportunity for Cheney students!
"Cooking with kids is not just about ingredients, recipes, and cooking. It's about harnessing imagination, empowerment, and creativity." -- Guy Fieri.

post_text:
Last week, Salnave Elementary School teacher Kyndle Palmer was selected as Eastern Washington University's Teacher of the Month from among all the teachers in Eastern Washington and Northern Idaho.
In an assembly on Friday, KHQ Wake Up Show anchors Leslie Lowe and Kalae Chock presented Ms. Palmer with the honor in an emotional surprise ceremony in front of the student body. Ms. Palmer teaches fourth and fifth-grade and was nominated by fifth-grader Emma Plewnarz.
“She’s so kind and she helps everyone else and she talks with people one on one,” Plewnarz said. “I sometimes stay in at last recess and talk with her and she’s just amazing.”
Ms. Palmer, who has been teaching for 10 years, called being selected a true honor. “I love working with my students,” she said. “They make such a difference in my life, too.”
We are so fortunate to have Ms. Palmer and so many other talented, caring teachers in our district!

Westwood Middle School CTE students were hard at work last week constructing large playhouses from the ground up. Teacher Marty Sexton said he got the idea when Principal Erika Burden told him about schools building tiny houses.
"But tiny houses have electrical, plumbing, etc., which would mean me doing a lot of things while they watched," he said. "I wanted to build things the kids could do all by themselves."
Career and technical education (CTE) is the practice of teaching specific career skills to students, and can help prepare them for work in trade and vocational fields. Sexton said several of his 17 students have seen increased engagement in his class and others. Once complete, the playhouses will be sold to recoup the cost of materials.
"If we could get $1,000 for them, that would be amazing," Sexton said. "Then we'd break even -- we're not expecting to make a profit."

A Cheney High School construction update:
Beginning today (Wednesday, Oct. 9) the high school's Main Entrance will be shifting away from the Little Theater/Science area. The new Main Entrance will essentially move back to what was the Main Entrance for many years at the front of the school.
Contractors have created a fenced, concrete pathway stretching from the Student Parking Lot to the Main Office area. This move will also open the end of the 200 Hallway that had been blocked.
An announcement was made to students at the end of the day yesterday. Thank you to all of the students and parents for being so patient and understanding of construction moves.

In regards to the heating issue at Cheney High School, administrators would like to thank staff, students and parents for their understanding and flexibility as the district deals with the unforeseen consequences of the sudden cold snap.
Superintendent Rob Roettger says the school contractor is devoting all resources to getting the boiler up and running as soon as possible. Initially it was planned to have the new boilers working by Oct. 7; thanks to their hard work, contractors hope to have the boilers running as soon as Wednesday morning. More updates and information to come.

On Thursday, October 3rd, Cheney Public Schools will be hosting community forums related to the upcoming proposed capital projects levy that is on the November 5th elections ballot. The forums will occur simultaneously in three separate locations across the district and each will begin at 6:00 p.m. The purpose of the forums is to share information and answer questions about the proposed capital levy. Meetings are open to the public and will be held at:

Sunset Elementary Library, 12824 W. 12th, Airway Heights

Westwood Middle School Commons, 6120 S. Abbott Rd., Spokane

Cheney Middle School Commons, 740 Betz Rd., Cheney

The forums will occur simultaneously in three separate locations across the district and each will begin at 6:00 p.m. The purpose of the forums is to share information and answer questions about the proposed capital levy. Meetings are open to the public and will be held at:

Sunset Elementary Library, 12824 W. 12th, Airway Heights

Westwood Middle School Commons, 6120 S. Abbott Rd., Spokane

Cheney Middle School Commons, 740 Betz Rd., Cheney

As the school year gets underway, please know that the immunization exclusion date is October 3, 2019. This means that all immunizations must be up to date and turned into your student’s school by the end of the school day on Thursday, October 3. Without proof of immunization compliance, the student will not be able to come back to class on Monday, October 7, and the student will remain excluded until proof of immunizations is provided to the school office.
See photo for immunization opportunities.

post_text: On August 19th, Westwood student leaders spent the day learning the difference between school climate and culture. Community partner Jacob Powers led an interactive session that focused on building meaningful relationships through strategic questioning. Students also learned active listening skills while having fun. The ASB and Wolverine Pride students looked at data to understand why being involved in school and having student to student relationships is important. With over 30 students in attendance, it was a great, early start to the 2019-2020 school year. Welcome back Wolverines!

post_text:
Betz Elementary Recognized by the State of Washington for Achievements

On Thursday, June 6, 2019, Betz Elementary was honored as a 2017-2018 State Recognized School for making some of the largest gains throughout the State of Washington based on the Washington School Improvement Framework measures. Betz students showed significant growth in Math proficiency, English Language Arts proficiency, and regular attendance. In addition, Betz narrowed the gaps between the highest and lowest performing student subgroups. Additional information on criteria and data collection can be found at: http://sbe.wa.gov/our-work/accountability/2017-2018-state-recognized-schools. Congratulations Betz students and staff!

post_text: Westwood art students recently started their painting class by studying the Abstract Expressionist art movement. After investigating the work of artists like Jackson Pollack and Wassily Kandinsky, students designed non-representational works to reflect their emotions, feelings, or thoughts. Symbolic colors, dynamic lines, and bold shapes characterize these paintings. The art offers powerful insight into the social and emotional state of middle school students.

post_text: Over the past couple of months, students at Westwood worked hard to compete at Science Olympiad. They competed on March 9th at SFCC and finished 7th out of 20 teams. Students competed in events that covered topics across all areas of science including building a battery powered car, creating a balsa wood glider, participating in knowledge events, and constructing a marble roller coaster. The students had a ton of fun and were able to learn a lot about science!

post_text: The Robotics Rumble at Lakeside High School is a robotics competition for middle and high school students. Students compete in a variety of course challenges with their BoeBot robot, which the student must code correctly to make it through without going out of bounds. This year there were over one hundred students and fifteen schools competing. Zach Cox, Keegan Lindsey and Nick Harper competed for Westwood Middle School. Zack Cox won 1st place in course navigation and 2nd place in best performance overall.

post_text:
Cheney Public Schools is pleased to announce that Windsor Elementary School paraeducator Kathy Larsen has been selected as the Classified Employee of the Year.

Kathy is being recognized for providing leadership, setting expectations, lending valuable perspectives, and being calm, kind and unflappable in all situations. She is consistently full of encouragement and support for staff and students alike.

Kathy is instrumental in the Windsor PAWS/PACE program, active on the PBIS committee, provides quality classified staff improvement opportunities, and is often “the rock” that staff and students lean on for guidance and accountability.

A few of the highlights that were shared about Kathy are “She is taking care of needs before we even know they exist”, “She is always mindful of student needs as well, nudging kids along the right path and thinking about how best to serve them”, and “…she works collaboratively to find a solution.” The District is blessed to have Mrs. Larsen on our team serving the students of Cheney Public Schools.
